exameP2
Class AssociativeArray<T>

java.lang.Object
  exameP2.AssociativeArray<T>

public class AssociativeArray<T>
extends java.lang.Object

Associative array with type String keys and generic elements.

This type of associative memory does not allow the existence of several elements with the same key. Instead, it behaves similarly to an array, in which a set to an existing key simply replaces the element to which the key is associated.

This class follows Design by Contract(tm) methodology.

Author:
Miguel Oliveira e Silva (mos@ua.pt)

Constructor Detail

AssociativeArray

public AssociativeArray()
Creates an empty associative array with the initial capacity of 1024 elements.

The created associative array has unlimited capacity, but it will be internally re-dimensioned whenever the load factor (size()/maximum-expected-capacity) exceeds 80%.

Postcondition:
isEmpty() - empty array.

AssociativeArray

public AssociativeArray(int expectedDim)
Creates an empty associative array with the dimensioned for a certain expected capacity.

The created associative array has unlimited capacity, but it will not change its internal expected capacity (regardless of the load factor).

Precondition:
expectedDim > 0 - positive dimension.
Postcondition:
isEmpty() - empty array.

Parameters:
expectedDim - associative array's expected capacity.

set

public void set(java.lang.String key,
                T elem)
Associates an element to a key in the associative array.

If the key does not exist, it creates a new association (increasing the array's size), otherwise it simply associates a new element to the existing key.

Precondition:
validKey(key)
Postcondition:
exists(key) - the key exists in the array.
get(key) == elem - the element is associated with the key

Parameters:
key - the key.
elem - element to associate to the key.
